> [{quoted}](name=Riot Tantram,realm=NA,application-id=ZGEFLEUQ,discussion-id=FxTLBeFc,comment-id=00000000000000010000,timestamp=2016-04-28T19:33:37.935+0000)
>
> Taunting a player for being in silver, repeatedly: &quot;400 games in silver say otherwise&quot; and &quot;I can see you&#x27;re upset about the 400 games, huh?&quot;
> More taunting: &quot;blaming region, that&#x27;s funny&quot;
> Taunting your jungler: &quot;Never seen a shaco lose jg to a lee sin before...&quot;
> Ganging up on the 2 people you have been harassing: &quot;Alistar is shaco&#x27;s waifu&quot;, &quot;Funny&quot;
> Passive aggressiveness towards others: &quot;Ali stop being toxic pls&quot;, &quot;Don&#x27;t forget to honor me for not getting tilted from all the negativity my team directed towards me ;)&quot;
> More taunting: &quot;So mad&quot;
> 
> And then the famous &quot;gg ez&quot;
> 
> You were trying to illicit a reaction through taunting and being passive aggressive.
> 
> All of this would have likely been a chat restriction if it was a consistent behavior. However, this was far from your first offense and as such it was escalated to the next level of punishment. Which in your case was a perma-ban .. the day after you got back from a 14-day ban.

Many of these quotes here are agreed upon by the community as undesired behavior.  I'm not going to lawyer here but there's an idea that "If the community agrees their behavior is wrong, and our system caught it, and they got banned" then victory is ours. We win. I don't see it that way. I just see it as the removal of another player from the community who, if we had a better system, may not have needed to be removed. Furthermore we've probably done them an injustice by being rather vague, strict and unwavering because those attributes of authority specifically don't meld well with people who are "taunting and being passive agressive".  

I'd really love to see some PhD level Psychological study done upon the implementational success of the tribunal (and I use that loosely) system and how it effects the majority population and outliers to it with specific regard to Psychological Disorders and the success rates it has with people who may have them.  It'd be my theory that, like our Justice Systems, there is a LOT to be desired when dealing with Mental Health and Psychological factors in specific regard to the concept of our punishment system being like "mandatory minimums" discriminating against those who may have mental health concerns.  As a very large company I don't think it's too much to ask that there should be a lot of thought placed into the moral and psychological implications of the system.  As a company, I know it's very important to focus on the results that make the system appear to be a full success and I'm not denying that it's done good. I just believe that it's a company's responsibility to continually build a better system and incorporate aspects of that system that allow it to be more understanding of the people it serves.

Just my two sense.

